AFTER five days of intense and tough challenges, the SAPS Special Task Force (STF) Unit proved they can hold their own against the best in the world. They recently took part in the annual five-day UAE SWAT Challenge in Dubai, which featured 55 teams from law enforcement agencies all over the world. And although they obtained ninth place with 183 points, which is an improvement from last year's 13th place, they are still number one in Africa. ALSO READ: Guards shot during heist The SWAT challenge assesses the tactical acumen, mental focus and physical endurance of law enforcement agencies from across the world and has been designed to promote the exchange of knowledge, expertise and to strengthen partnerships to make communities safe. The teams overall commander, the component head responsible for specialised pperations, Major General Nonhlanhla Zulu, who formed part of the team in Dubai said the SAPS is proud of the team. “The members’ performance is commendable. In the world we are number nine, but on the African continent we are number one, so this is a big achievement. We beat Kenya and Libya. So yes, we are satisfied with the results. We hope to do better next time. We are happy to be back to continue to deal decisively with serious and violent crime in our country,” said Zulu. REGISTER TO COMMENT The Special Task Force is a highly specialised unit in the SAPS whose members are responsible for only responding to high-risk incidents, which include hostage-taking cases, search and rescue missions, as well as providing specialised operational support to other units within the SAPS. #sapsHQ #SAPS Special Task Force Unit has made it onto top 10 of world’s best SWAT teams. Team obtained 9th place @ #UAESWATChallengein Dubai. They retain their position as Number 1 SWAT team in Africa. STF responds to high-risk incidents, #CIT, etc. TMhttps://t.co/W7qyCD6LXM pic.twitter.com/fnRp2LfaFU 